Here's how to set up switchable branded themes in .NET MAUI:

## 1. Define Resource Dictionaries for each theme

Create separate XAML resource dictionaries:

**Themes/LightTheme.xaml**
```xml
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
    <!-- Add more colors, styles, etc. -->
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**Themes/DarkTheme.xaml** and **Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml** follow the same pattern with different values.

## 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public static class ThemeService
{
    public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDictionaries = Application.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
        mergedDictionaries.Clear();

        var themeDictionary = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new Themes.LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDictionaries.Add(themeDictionary);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

## 3. Apply on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:
```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
    MainPage = new AppShell();
}
```

## 4. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Choose Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>High Contrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var theme = ThemePicker.SelectedIndex switch
    {
        1 => ThemeService.AppTheme.Dark,
        2 => ThemeService.AppTheme.HighContrast,
        _ => ThemeService.AppTheme.Light
    };
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

## 5. Use theme keys with DynamicResource

This is **critical** — use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so values update at runtime:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" />
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
```

## Key points

- **`DynamicResource`** enables live switching without restarting the app.
- **`Preferences`** persists the user's choice across sessions.
- Keep the same `x:Key` names consistent across all three dictionaries so bindings resolve regardless of which theme is active.
- You can extend this with `Style` definitions inside each theme dictionary for controls like buttons, entries, etc.
